          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Reasoning Benchmarks"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Reasoning benchmarks test the cognitive core of an agentic system: the ability to "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "derive correct conclusions from given premises",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "bold"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " without relying on memorized facts. They are important for agent evaluation because many failure modes — hallucinated steps, wrong plans, incorrect arithmetic — trace back to weak reasoning rather than missing knowledge. A model that reasons reliably is less dependent on retrieval and less likely to confidently produce a wrong answer."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Benchmark Landscape"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "image",
        "attrs": {
          "src": "data:image/svg+xml;base64,",
          "alt": "Reasoning benchmarks: ARC-AGI, MATH/AIME, HotpotQA/MuSiQue, StrategyQA/LogiQA"
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Reasoning benchmarks span five types of reasoning. Each type demands a different agent strategy and different tool use, so a model's score on one benchmark does not predict its score on another."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "ARC-AGI: Abstract and Reasoning Corpus"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "ARC-AGI (François Chollet, 2019) presents 1,000 tasks as input/output grid pairs. The model must infer the transformation rule from 3-5 examples and apply it to a new input. No world knowledge helps — every task is solvable from the examples alone with pure inductive reasoning."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "bulletList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Each task: 3-5 (input, output) grid examples + 1 test input. Grids are up to 30×30 cells with 10 possible colors."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Score: exact match on the predicted output grid. Partial credit is not given."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Public test set: 400 tasks. Private test set: 600 tasks (evaluation via ARC Prize submission)."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Human baseline: ~98% — humans solve almost all tasks in minutes using pattern recognition."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "SOTA (2024): ~55% (OpenAI o3 with high compute). Most models score 20-40%."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Loading and Evaluating ARC-AGI"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "import json\nfrom pathlib import Path\nfrom datasets import load_dataset\n\n# Public evaluation set\narc = load_dataset(\"allenai/arc_challenge\", split=\"test\")  # ARC-Challenge (proxy)\n\n# For ARC-AGI specifically, use the official dataset:\n# https://github.com/fchollet/ARC-AGI\n# Load from local clone:\ndef load_arc_agi(data_dir: str) -> list[dict]:\n    tasks = []\n    for path in sorted(Path(data_dir).glob(\"*.json\")):\n        data = json.loads(path.read_text())\n        tasks.append({\n            \"task_id\": path.stem,\n            \"train\": data[\"train\"],   # list of {input, output} pairs\n            \"test\": data[\"test\"],     # list of {input} (output is held out)\n        })\n    return tasks\n\ndef format_arc_task(task: dict) -> str:\n    lines = []\n    for i, ex in enumerate(task[\"train\"]):\n        lines.append(f\"Example {i+1} input: {ex['input']}\")\n        lines.append(f\"Example {i+1} output: {ex['output']}\")\n    lines.append(f\"Test input: {task['test'][0]['input']}\")\n    lines.append(\"What is the test output?\")\n    return \"\\n\".join(lines)\n"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "import anthropic, json, ast\n\nclient = anthropic.Anthropic()\n\ndef solve_arc_task(task: dict, model=\"claude-haiku-4-5-20251001\") -> list[list[int]]:\n    prompt = format_arc_task(task)\n    system = (\n        \"You solve ARC-AGI grid transformation tasks. \"\n        \"Study the input/output examples, infer the rule, apply it to the test input. \"\n        \"Return only the output grid as a JSON 2D array of integers. No explanation.\"\n    )\n    resp = client.messages.create(\n        model=model,\n        max_tokens=512,\n        system=system,\n        messages=[{\"role\": \"user\", \"content\": prompt}],\n    )\n    raw = resp.content[0].text.strip()\n    try:\n        return json.loads(raw)\n    except json.JSONDecodeError:\n        # Attempt ast.literal_eval as fallback for Python-style lists\n        try:\n            return ast.literal_eval(raw)\n        except Exception:\n            return []\n\ndef score_arc(predictions: list, ground_truths: list) -> float:\n    correct = sum(1 for p, g in zip(predictions, ground_truths) if p == g)\n    return correct / len(ground_truths)\n"
          }
        ]
      },
